<section id="the-problem" data-test="problem-section" style="padding:5rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-surface);">
  <div style="max-width:48rem;margin:0 auto;">
    <h2 style="font-size:clamp(1.5rem,4vw,2.25rem);font-weight:700;margin:0 0 1.25rem;color:var(--color-text);">The Problem: Spec Drift</h2>
    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 1rem;">
      When you prompt an AI agent to "build a task manager," the agent makes hundreds of micro-decisions — what to name fields, how to handle edge cases, what the UI looks like. These decisions diverge from your intent, and there's no shared artifact to catch the drift.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 1rem;">
      Traditional specs (PRDs, Figma mocks, Jira tickets) aren't machine-readable. They can't be tested. So agents ignore them, interpret them loosely, or contradict them silently.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:1.05rem;color:var(--color-text-muted);line-height:1.7;margin:0;">
      The result is software that approximately matches what you wanted — good enough to demo, but wrong in the details that matter.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
